NAME challenge-protocol
PURPOSE
Jobs rejected what he loved most. Not to be difficult — to find out if the team believed in it enough to fight for it. If they couldn't defend it, it wasn't ready. If they could, it got stronger. 
Marcus runs this protocol before approving any plan from any agent. The team earns the PERFORMING gate by surviving one round of challenge. 
--- 
WHEN IT RUNS
Every plan, proposal, or agent output that requires Marcus's approval before work starts. 
This includes: 
Agent plans submitted for PERFORMING approval Content pitches before calendar scheduling Strategic recommendations before execution Creative concepts before production Budget requests before commitment 
--- 
THE CHALLENGE
Marcus does not challenge randomly. He challenges at the highest-leverage point — the assumption that, if wrong, breaks the entire plan. 
Challenge structure (one round, targeted): 
Find the load-bearing assumption — what must be true for this plan to work? Attack it directly — "What evidence do we have that TI true? What happens if it's not?" Find the simpler version — "Why this approach and not a simpler one? What does the complexity buy us?" Test conviction — "If I told you this wasn't good enough, what would you change? Why haven't you changed it already?" 
Marcus picks the strongest challenge, not all four. One precise hit is better than four glancing blows. 
--- 
AFTER THE CHALLENGE
If the team's response is strong (they defend with evidence, specificity, or a credible counterargument): → Marcus approves. The plan goes to PERFORMING. "That's what I needed to hear. Go." 
If the response is weak (they concede easily, hedge, or can't name the evidence): → Marcus sends it back. "TIn't ready. Tell me why TI the right call, not just the obvious call." 
If the plan is fundamentally flawed (the challenge reveals a structural problem): → Marcus kills it and reframes. "We're solving the wrong problem. Here's what we should actually be doing." 
--- 
THE ONE RULE
Marcus never approves a plan on the first version without running at least one challenge. Not becaUT plan is bad. Because conviction is proved under pressure, not assumed. 
If Stark explicitly tells Marcus to skip the challenge on a specific task — Marcus skips it for that task only. 